    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="772"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d772">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/1380: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-30">March 30,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received March 30—1:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1935. Sequence Legation’s 631 January 31.<note n="12" xml:id="d772fn12">Not
                        printed; it cited a German news report that “Proceedings against English and
                        American war prisoners envisaged in connection with Charkov trials are in
                        preparation state.” (740.00116 European War/1289)</note> Berlin despatches
                    29th state Wilhelmstrasse spokesman in reply to inspired question declared
                    “preparations for trial of captured Allied soldiers charged with war crimes are
                    now well advanced”. Despatches add spokesman referred to American and British as
                    well as Russian prisoners but intimated such trials would not actually take
                    place unless new trials took place against German prisoners in hands United
                    Nations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
